  noria:locatedAtLocus <https://example.com/locus1> ;
  noria:resourceManagedBy <https://example.com/Org1> .

# Hub node: central, high-degree node connected to multiple entities
<https://example.com/entity1> noria:connectedTo <https://example.com/entity2> , <https://example.com/entity3> , <https://example.com/entity4> .

# High-degree node: resource with many relations
<https://example.com/entity2> noria:connectedTo <https://example.com/entity1> , <https://example.com/entity3> .

# Central node: application linking multiple resources and services
<https://example.com/app1> noria:relatedResource <https://example.com/Resource1> , <https://example.com/Resource2> .

# Connector node: resource connecting network links
<https://example.com/Resource2> noria:connectedTo <https://example.com/NetworkLink1> .

# Intermediary node: application mediating between resources and services
<https://example.com/app1> noria:applicationRelatedResource <https://example.com/Resource1> .

# Multiplex node: resource involved in multiple relations
<https://example.com/Resource1> noria:connectedTo <https://example.com/Resource2> , <https://example.com/Resource3> .

# Super node: resource with extensive relations
<https://example.com/entity1> noria:connectedTo <https://example.com/entity2> , <https://example.com/entity3> , <https://example.com/entity4> , <https://example.com/entity5> .

# Dismiss isolated nodes: all nodes have at least one relation, as above.
